            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Irina Petrova\u2019s life is measured in the steady rumble of a MUNI bus engine, a rhythm far removed from her beginnings in Perm, Russia. Born in the shadow of the crumbling Soviet Union, her childhood was defined by pragmatism. Her father, a factory mechanic, and mother, a ledger clerk, instilled in her a simple ethos: work hard, expect little, and rely on yourself. She completed her secondary schooling and, seeing few other paths, began driving a trolleybus, mastering the heavy vehicle on icy, potholed streets.\n\nThe major turning point in her life arrived via an early internet dating site. She met a charismatic American software engineer from the Bay Area who promised a new world. At 25, fueled by a cautious optimism, she married him and immigrated to San Francisco. The California dream, however, quickly soured. The cultural chasm was vast; her husband\u2019s world of tech startups and fleeting social circles felt alienating compared to her grounded upbringing. The marriage ended in a quiet, painful divorce after four years, leaving Irina with a green card but a shattered sense of direction.\n\nFacing the prospect of returning to Russia in defeat, her innate resilience kicked in. She drew on her one marketable skill, applying for a position as a MUNI bus driver. The union job offered stability she desperately craved. She passed the training and was assigned a route that snaked through the very city that had almost broken her.\n\nNow 41, Irina lives a life of disciplined routine. Her small, tidy apartment in the Inner Richmond is just a short walk from her depot, hence her zero-mile commute. Her days start before dawn with strong black tea. On the road, she is a silent observer, watching the city\u2019s diverse cast of characters from behind the protective glass. She knows the regulars\u2014the elderly woman heading to Chinatown, the student with the heavy backpack, the construction worker with paint-splattered boots.\n\nHer social circle is small, consisting mostly of a few other Russian-speaking women she meets for groceries at the New World Market. She is guarded but not unkind. Her hopes are no longer grand American dreams, but tangible goals: to one day buy her modest apartment, to maintain her health, and to find a quiet, consistent peace. Driving her bus up and down San Francisco's hills, Irina has navigated more than just city streets; she has charted a course for a life of her own making, finding solace in the predictable journey."
